    <p>For most independent freelancers, <strong>Net 15 is the right default</strong>. It is short enough to keep cash flowing and to surface payment problems early, but long enough that corporate AP departments do not feel rushed. Reserve Net 30 for clients who explicitly require it (most large companies will), and Net 45 or Net 60 only for high-value contracts where the project economics justify the cash flow strain.</p>

    <h2>Late Fees and How to Use Them</h2>
    <p>Late fees serve two purposes: they compensate you for the cost of waiting for money you have already earned, and they create a financial incentive for clients to pay on time. The standard freelance late fee is 1.5 percent per month of the unpaid balance, which annualizes to 18 percent. Some freelancers charge a flat fee (25 to 50 dollars) for the first instance of lateness and switch to percentage-based fees if the delay continues.</p>
    <p>Late fees only work if three things are true. First, your written contract or engagement agreement must clearly state the late fee policy before work begins. Surprising a client with a late fee they never agreed to is unprofessional and unenforceable. Second, the late fee must be stated on the invoice itself, in the payment terms section. Third, your state's usury laws must allow the rate you are charging — most states cap interest at 10 to 24 percent annually for non-bank lenders. A 1.5 percent monthly fee (18 percent annual) is within legal limits in nearly all states, but check your local law if you go higher.</p>
    <p>In practice, late fees are mostly a deterrent and a negotiating tool, not a revenue source. Freelancers commonly waive late fees for clients who eventually pay, and reserve them for clients who have become seriously delinquent. The mere existence of a late fee on your invoice often motivates payment without the fee ever being applied.</p>
    <p>A common alternative to late fees is offering an early payment discount — for example, "2 percent discount if paid within 10 days of invoice date, otherwise full amount due in 30 days." This is the "2/10 Net 30" notation in formal accounting. Early payment discounts work especially well with clients who would not be motivated by late fees but who do pay attention to small efficiencies.</p>

    <h2>Recurring Invoices and Retainers</h2>
    <p>For ongoing client relationships, recurring invoices and retainer agreements dramatically reduce both your admin time and the risk of payment delays. Instead of negotiating, scoping, and invoicing each piece of work separately, you bill a fixed amount on a regular schedule (monthly is most common) for an agreed scope of work or available hours.</p>
    <p>Retainers benefit both parties. The client gets predictable access to your services and predictable monthly cost. You get predictable cash flow, which is the single biggest advantage you can give your freelance business. A handful of retainer clients can stabilize an otherwise volatile income, making it easier to plan, save, and invest.</p>
    <p>Set up retainers carefully. Define exactly what is included (number of hours, specific deliverables, response time guarantees), what is excluded (rush work, weekends, scope outside the agreed services), and how unused hours roll over (or do not). Bill at the start of each month rather than the end — clients are more likely to pay for service they are about to receive than service they have already consumed.</p>
    <p>Most invoicing software supports automatic recurring invoices that send themselves on a fixed schedule. Setting this up once and letting it run for the duration of the engagement saves hours of monthly admin and eliminates the "did I send the invoice yet?" question.</p>

